      "ai_preview": {
        "text": "**Brazil roll into World Cup 2026 as the heavy favorites, but they're doing it without their two biggest attacking weapons.** Neymar and Vinícius Jr. are both out, which stings—but the Seleção still have enough firepower to make noise in Group Stage. Morocco arrive unbeaten in their last five (3W 2D) and won't be a pushover, especially with A. Hakimi running down that flank. 🔥\n\nBrazil's form is slick when they're at home (6-2 over Panama, 2-1 over Egypt), though that loss to Croatia away shows they can be caught. Morocco's draws against Norway hint at defensive solidity, but their big wins came against minnows. The absence of Neymar and Vinícius Jr. might actually slow Brazil's usual attacking tempo.\n\nKey storylines:\n\n- **Raphinha and M. Cunha** inherit the creative burden with the star wingers sidelined—this is their moment to shine in an open group\n- **Morocco's backline** anchored by N. Aguerd and I. Diop will need to weather sustained pressure from a Brazil midfield spearheaded by **Casemiro**\n- **A. Hakimi** in transition could be dangerous on the counter if Brazil get too adventurous early\n\nExpected lineups:\n\n- **Brazil**: Alisson, D. Santos, Marquinhos, L. Pereira, A. Sandro, Casemiro, B. Guimarães, Raphinha, M. Cunha, L. Henrique, I. Thiago\n- **Morocco**: Bono, A. Salah-Eddine, N. Aguerd, I. Diop, A. Hakimi, N. El Aynaoui, I. Saibari, A. Ounahi, B. E. Khannouss, B. Díaz, A. E. Kaabi\n\nBest picks:\n\n- **Total Goals Under 3.5**: Under 3.5 goals\n\nPrediction:\n\n**Brazil 2–0 Morocco.** Brazil edge this opener without their star attackers, but Morocco's shape keeps it tight. ⚽",
